Encapsulation ğŸ”’

Encapsulation is the concept of bundling data and methods that operate on that data within a single unit, called a class ğŸ“¦. This helps to:

Hide internal implementation details from the outside world ğŸ¤«
Protect data from external interference and misuse ğŸš«
Improve code organization and readability ğŸ“–
Abstraction ğŸ”®

Abstraction is the practice of exposing only essential features of an object while hiding its internal complexities ğŸ”. This enables:

Simplified interactions with complex systems ğŸ“ˆ
Improved modularity and reusability of code ğŸ“¦
Easier maintenance and updates ğŸ’»
Getters and Setters ğŸ”‘

Getters and setters are special methods that allow controlled access to an object's properties ğŸ”“. They provide a way to:

Validate input data ğŸ“
Perform additional logic before setting or retrieving data ğŸ’¡
Maintain data integrity and consistency ğŸ’¯
Abstract Classes and Interfaces ğŸ“‹

Abstract classes and interfaces define blueprints for other classes to follow ğŸ“. They provide a way to:

Define a common set of methods and properties for related classes ğŸ‘¥
Establish a contract that must be implemented by derived classes ğŸ“
Promote code reuse and polymorphism ğŸ”
Interfaces ğŸ“

Interfaces are abstract classes that contain only method declarations, without any implementation ğŸ“. They are used to:

Define a set of methods that must be implemented by derived classes ğŸ‘‰
Establish a contract for other classes to follow ğŸ“
Promote loose coupling and polymorphism ğŸ”
